Based on the experimental setup and measurement method discussed in Sections 2.5 and 2.6, the representative Nyquist EIS testing plots of the resistances of configured coin cells with compressed PP and PE separators in electrolyte were respectively shown in Fig. 4 (b) and (c), in which the intercept of the curve with the x-axis gives the resistance of the configured coin cell (R

                           cell
                        ). It can be observed that the Nyquist plots exhibit a curvature near the intersection at the real axis, which becomes obvious gradually with the increase of the specified compressive stress, especially for the PP at the 60 MPa (see the insert in Fig. 4 (b)). Based on the Randles equivalent circuit [48], the high and low frequency responses of the circuit are governed by charge transfer and diffusion, respectively [49]. Therefore, this phenomenon can be attributed to the decreased connectivity of the pore space in the separator, which leads to a sabotage of the charge transfer of the electrolyte in the separator at high frequency response. The tortuosity against the strain is calculated using Eqs. (1)–(3), as shown in Fig. 4 (d), which clearly shows that the increase of the compressive strain leads to the increases of the ion passage lengths through the porous separator, i.e., the tortuosity. The tortuosity of the PE separator increases slowly with the increase of compressive strain before the strain reaches the onset strain of densification, while the tortuosity of the PP separator starts to increase quickly at a compressive strain before the onset strain of densification. The different results for PP and PE separators discussed above can be attributed to their different microstructures (see Fig. 2 (d), (e) and (g), (h)) i.e. the lamellae of PP separator oriented along TTD can provide good compressive stress resistance while the multilayer structure of PE separator is uniformly distributed along TTD and shows moderate resistance of compressive stress before densification. As a result, the collapsed lamellae of PP separator along TTD increases the path length in the porous structure, and thus leads to a higher tortuosity before PP separator enters the densification regime. Furthermore, compared with the surface view of PE separator (see Fig. 2 (e) and (h)), the PP separator has much more amount of lamellae than PE separator. Therefore, the widened lamellae in the compressed PP separator can dramatically decrease the pore area contacted to the electrode and lead to higher tortuosity during compression process even though it does not reach the onset strain of densification.
